# SpecRow Agent Install Instructions

Use this file when the user asks an agent to apply SpecRow from:

apply https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nektobit/SpecRow/refs/heads/main/install language=<language-code>

Follow these steps in the current project root.

1. Determine the project language.

Use the explicit `language=<language-code>` argument from the user's apply command when present:

```txt
apply https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nektobit/SpecRow/refs/heads/main/install language=ru
```

When an explicit `language=<language-code>` argument is present, immediately switch your own replies, status updates, questions, and final installation report to that language before continuing with the rest of this install flow. Use the same language for any SpecRow files you create or revise. Do not wait until after `specrow init` to change language.

If `.specrow/config.yml` already exists, read its `language` field and keep that language unless the user explicitly asks to change it.

If `.specrow/config.yml` provides the language and no explicit apply argument overrides it, immediately use that configured language for your replies, status updates, questions, final installation report, and any SpecRow files you create or revise.

If neither source is available, ask the user which working language to use before running `specrow init`. Ask that question in the user's current conversation language. Supported built-in languages are `en`, `ru`, `es`, and `zh-CN`. Do not silently choose English for a new project when the language is ambiguous.

2. Check whether the SpecRow CLI is available.

```bash
specrow --version
```

3. If the command is missing, install SpecRow.

Prefer the user's existing Node.js package manager if the project makes it obvious. Otherwise use npm:

```bash
npm i -g specrow
```

If package installation requires approval, ask the user before installing.

4. Initialize the SpecRow workspace if `.specrow/config.yml` does not exist.

Pass the determined language explicitly:

```bash
specrow init --language <language-code>
```

5. Install agent integrations.

If you can identify your agent environment, pass the matching tool name:

```bash
specrow integrate --tools codex
specrow integrate --tools claude
specrow integrate --tools cursor
specrow integrate --tools windsurf
```

If you cannot identify the current agent reliably, let SpecRow detect it:

```bash
specrow integrate --detect
```

For a portable fallback that any agent can read, install generic instructions:

```bash
specrow integrate --tools generic
```

6. Validate the workspace and report what changed.

```bash
specrow validate
specrow integrations status
```

Tell the user which integrations were installed and whether their IDE or agent needs to be restarted before new commands, prompts, skills, rules, or workflows appear.

Do not implement project code as part of this install flow unless the user separately asks for a SpecRow change workflow such as `/specrow:proposal` or `/specrow:build`.
